# README Conventions

## Badge Rules

- Always use `img.shields.io` for badges — NEVER `custom-icon-badges.demolab.com` (unreliable, frequently down)
- Every package README must include: GitHub stars, npm version, npm downloads, bundle size, license, TypeScript badge
- Badges go in a centered `<p align="center">` block right after the title
- Adapter packages should add a technology badge (Firebase, GraphQL, Axios, OpenAPI, etc.)

## Title & Visual Identity

- Titles use emoji + human-friendly name: `# ⚡ Hyper Fetch`, NOT `# @hyper-fetch/core`
- Each package has its own emoji (keep them consistent):
  - ⚡ core, ⚛️ react, 🛰️ sockets, 🪄 cli, 🏛️ axios, 🔥 firebase/firebase-admin, 🎡 graphql, 🔧 devtools plugin, ⚛️ hyper-flow, 🧹 eslint, 🧪 testing
- Subtitle goes in a centered `<p align="center"><b>...</b></p>` right after the title
- READMEs must look visually appealing — emojis in section headers, bold key terms in capabilities

## Section Order (strict)

Every package README follows this exact section order:

1. `# {emoji} {Name}` — Title with emoji
2. `<p align="center"><b>...</b></p>` — One-line value proposition
3. Badges block (centered)
4. `## 📖 About` — 2-3 sentences: what it does, who it's for, what problem it solves
5. `## 🎯 Key Capabilities` — Persuasive feature list (see rules below)
6. `## 🚀 Quick Start` — Install command + 3-8 lines of working code
7. `## 📚 Documentation` — Links to docs, guides, API reference
8. `## 💡 Examples` — Rich, package-specific code examples (ALWAYS last content section)
9. `## License` — MIT link

## Key Capabilities Rules (CRITICAL)

Key capabilities are the MOST IMPORTANT part of the README. They sell the package.

### Tone & Style
- Write from the USER's perspective — what problems do THEY stop having?
- Short, punchy, benefit-first — not technical descriptions
- Use emoji + **bold label** + dash + benefit: `- 🔮 **Zero guesswork** — Full autocompletion for every request, response, param, and error`
- Each bullet should make someone think "I need this"
- NO generic filler like "Simple setup", "Easy to use", "Flexible" — these say nothing

### Content Rules
- List 4-10 capabilities per package (more for core, fewer for small adapters)
- Lead with the most impressive/unique capability
- Focus on pain points solved: broken types? manual clients? debugging hell? offline crashes?
- Include the specific HyperFetch feature name when relevant (e.g. `useFetch`, `createRequest`)
- Keep each bullet to ONE line — if it wraps, it's too long

### What NOT to write
- ❌ "Simple setup" — everyone claims this
- ❌ "Easy to use" — means nothing
- ❌ "Flexible" — too vague
- ❌ "Built-in adapter" — not a user benefit
- ❌ Feature lists copied from other packages — each README must have UNIQUE capabilities

## About Section Rules

- 2-3 sentences maximum
- First sentence: what the package IS (identity)
- Second sentence: what it DOES for the user (benefit)
- Optional third sentence: how it relates to the ecosystem
- NO bullet lists in About — that's what Key Capabilities is for

## Quick Start Rules

- Install command first (npm install)
- Then a WORKING code snippet (3-8 lines, copy-pasteable)
- Must demonstrate the core use case of this specific package
- Include TypeScript types in the example to show type safety

## Examples Rules

- Examples section is ALWAYS the last content section (before License)
- Each example must be a real, practical use case — not toy code
- Show things users actually do: auth, forms, pagination, error handling
- Use descriptive `### Sub-heading` for each example
- At least 2 examples per package (except testing/eslint which can have 1)

## Root README Special Rules

- Uses hero image at the top
- Centered tagline: "One SDK. Any API. Fully typed."
- Two quick start paths: manual setup + CLI generation
- "Why HyperFetch?" section with 4 benefit bullets
- Packages table with version/downloads/size badges (markdown table, not HTML)
- Sponsor section preserved

## Formatting Rules

- NEVER use em dashes (`—`) anywhere in READMEs. Use a regular dash (`-`) or rewrite the sentence instead.
